Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Kenya Power; United Bank for Africa

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-12-01T15:54:21Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-12-01/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-kenya-power-united-bank-for-africa.html
Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index (SEMDEX)  dropped for
a 12th day, erasing 0.2 percent to 1,859.94 by the close, the
longest decline since the 14 days through Aug. 28, 2008.  Kenya’s  All-Share Index (NSEASI)  fell for a sixth day, weakening 0.3
percent to 53.61 in Nairobi, the longest losing streak since the
11 days through Oct. 3. The  Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index 
snapped three days of gains, tumbling 0.9 percent to 978.77 in
Accra. The  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  advanced for the sixth
day, rising 0.8 percent to 846.54 in Windhoek, the highest since
July 26. The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index (NGSEINDX)  slid 0.2
percent to 19,967.84 in Lagos, according to an e-mailed
statement from the bourse.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Kenya Power & Lighting Ltd. (KPLL)  , the East African
nation’s sole electricity distributor, fell for a third day,
tumbling 3 percent to 16.2 shillings, the lowest close since
January 2010.  “Kenya Power is mostly being traded by retail investors
and with inflation rising we have been seeing some selling from
them,” Deris Mogoi, a research analyst at Standard Investment
Bank Ltd. in Nairobi, said by phone today.  United Bank for Africa Plc (UBA)  , the Nigerian lender
with operations in 19 African countries, declined 0.8 percent to
2.53 naira. The Lagos-based bank said it plans to reduce it
share capital to 6.5 billion naira from 16.2 billion naira in a
restructuring. The share capital will then be increased to 16.2
billion naira by creating 19.4 billion new shares of 50 kobo
each, according to a statement published today in Nigerian
Thisday newspaper.  To contact the reporter on this story:
